ave sought to take their cue from Kant, Wittgenstein, or Cavell - and to illuminate how these philosophical approaches are related to and bear upon one another. The philosophers brought together in this volume are united by the thought that a proper appreciation of the depth of the skeptical challenge must reveal it to be deeply disquieting, in the sense that skepticism threatens not just some set of theoretical commitments, but also-and fundamentally-our very sense of self, world, and other. Second, that skepticism is the proper starting point for any serious attempt to make sense of what philosophy is, and to gauge the prospects of philosophical progress.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aSkepticism. 4aBedeutung. 4aCavell, Stanley. 4aErkenntnis. 4aKant, Imanuel. 4aWittgenstein, Ludwig. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh  aMeaning, knowledge, Kant, Immanuel, Cavell, Stanley, Wittgenstein, Ludwig.1 aAffeldt, Steven G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBridges, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConant, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConant, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDiamond, Cora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranks, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlendinning, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamawaki, Arata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKern, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKern, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMenke, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo